             PLASTRIERE. I am a watch-maker. I look at the watch given by the prisoner to the prosecutor; it is a very common watch; it is capped with a mock jewel, and may be worth thirty-eight or forty shillings.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160110-27-person264">
                  JOHN 
                  DICKSON SMITH
               <interp inst="t18160110-27-person264" type="surname" value="DICKSON SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160110-27-person264" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18160110-27-person264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . At a quarter before two, last Tuesday week, I saw a crowd at the foot of the watchhouse, and I saw a sailor had hold of the prisoner, who was charged with robbing him of his watch, in Oxford-street. I found these two watches on him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18160110-27-person265">
                  Isaac 
                  Le Plastriere
               <interp inst="t18160110-27-person265" type="surname" value="Le Plastriere"></interp>
